# Jaclyn Chua _v_ Control Automation Pte Ltd  

### \[2022\] SGDC 97

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Court Suit No 2570 of 2018, Summons No 541 of 2022 and 484 of 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">12 May 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Kim Bumsoo</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Joseph Liow (Joseph Liow LLP) (instructed), Rajvant Kaur d/o Jagit Singh (Omnia Law Chambers LLC) for the plaintiff and defendants in counterclaim; Pua Lee Siang (Kelvin Chia Partnership) for the defendant and plaintiff in counterclaim</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Jaclyn Chua — Control Automation Pte Ltd — Boo Choon Chik (trading as J &amp; J Automation)</td></tr></tbody></table>

Civil Procedure – Pleadings – Striking out

Civil Procedure – Discovery of documents

12 May 2022 - Judgment reserved.

### Deputy Registrar Kim Bum Soo:

1       Deny during discovery and produce when pressed. That was the theme of the Plaintiff’s (“**Chua**”) conduct during discovery. Throughout these proceedings, Chua proved to be evasive and recalcitrant, shifting her position constantly on everything from the relevance of the documents requested, to her possession of these documents and finally, in the hearings before me, the very existence of the documents themselves. Her conduct was egregious enough to warrant an unless order (“**the Unless Order**”). Now, pursuant to this order, the Defendant and Plaintiff in Counterclaim (“**CAPL**”) has brought DC/SUM 541/2022 (“**SUM 541**”) seeking to strike out Chua’s entire claim and defence to counterclaim.

2       I agree with CAPL that Chua’s conduct fell short of her discovery obligations. The Unless Order was breached. However, a complete striking out would be excessive and disproportionate. As such, I am minded only to strike out the defence to CAPL’s counterclaim.

3       Ultimately, proportionality is the touchstone for any Court tasked with imposing sanctions for breach of an unless order: _Mitora Pte Ltd v Agritrade International (Pte.) Ltd._ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 3 SLR 1179</span> at \[39\] (“_Mitora_”). No doubt, a complete striking out would vindicate CAPL’s (understandable) frustrations. But it would also risk being unduly penal, and an unless order’s purpose is “not to punish misconduct but to secure a fair trial in accordance with due process of law”: _Mitora_ at \[45\]. A more surgical approach, having regard to the actual prejudice suffered by CAPL, was therefore the more appropriate way of addressing these breaches. I explain further below.

## Facts

### The parties and their dispute

4       Chua is CAPL’s ex-director. She left CAPL sometime in July 2017 and ran a separate business called J&J Automation (“**J&J**”) with her husband (the 2nd Defendant in Counterclaim, “**Boon**”).

5       Chua’s claim against CAPL is for her unpaid salaries from July 2017 to August 2017.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) CAPL denies owing her anything and claims that the unpaid salaries (if any at all) should be set off against other sums it is owed. CAPL’s counterclaim, among other things, is that J&J has been siphoning business from CAPL.[^2] Chua therefore breached her employment contract with CAPL (“**the Employment Contract**”), her obligations as a trustee of CAPL’s assets and her duties as CAPL’s director. Chua’s main response to this is that J&J was operated with CAPL’s full knowledge and was in fact, set up with CAPL’s managing director’s (“**Leong**”) blessing.

### The procedural history

6       On 30 September 2021, Deputy Registrar Lewis Tan partially granted CAPL’s application for specific discovery. His order was extracted as DC/ORC 3490/2021 (“**The Discovery Order**”). These covered 16 categories of documents and broadly pertained to CAPL’s counterclaim.

7       On 21 January 2022, Deputy Registrar Elaine Lim (“**DR Lim**”) granted an unless order against Chua and Boon (this being the Unless Order described above), requiring them to comply fully with the Discovery Order save as to 3 of the 16 categories listed in the Discovery Order. Failing compliance, the Unless Order threatened to strike out “the Statement of Claim filed on 15 March 2018 and Reply and Defence to Counterclaim (Amendment No. 2) filed on 20 May 2021 \[…\] with costs of the Action and Counterclaim to be paid by the 1st and 2nd Defendants in Counterclaim to the Plaintiff in Counterclaim”.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3)

## Issues to be determined

8       The main issues are:

> (a)     Whether there was a breach of the Unless Order; and

> (b)     Whether the claim and defence to counterclaim ought to be struck out.

## Issue 1: Whether there was a breach of the Unless Order

9       The Unless Order stated that:

> 1\. Unless the 1st and 2nd Defendants in Counterclaim comply fully with \[the Discovery Order\] (except in relation to Annex A, Category 5 and Annex B, Gategories 9 and 10 thereof) \[by 4 February 2022\], the Statement of Claim filed on 15 March 2018 and Reply and Defence to Counterclaim (Amendment No. 2) filed on 20 May 2021 be struck out with costs of the Action and Counterclaim to be paid by the 1st and 2nd Defendants in Counterclaim to the Plaintiff in Counterclaim.

> …

10     The Discovery Order was worded as follows:

> 1.    That \[Chua\] does, within 7 days from the date of this Order of Court, file and serve a supplemental list of documents listing the documents stated in “Annex A" and “Annex B" annexed hereto which \[Chua\] has or had in her possession, custody or power, and in relation to the documents which she has had but no longer has in her possession, custody or power, stating when she had them and what has become of them, together with an affidavit verifying such list;

> 2.    That \[Boon\] does, within 7 days from the date of this Order of Court, file and serve a supplemental list of documents listing the documents stated in “Annex A" and “Annex B" annexed hereto which \[Boon\] has or had in his possession, custody or power, and in relation to the documents which he has had but no longer has in his possession, custody or power, stating when he had them and what has become of them, together with an affidavit verifying such list;

> 3.    That there be inspection of the aforesaid documents within 7 days of the service of the aforesaid supplemental lists of documents and affidavits verifying such lists

> …

11     The Annexes described in the Discovery Order have been tabulated here for ease of reference. I have also indicated (with strikethrough) those items that DR Lim found to have already been disclosed:

12     There are two alleged breaches.

> (a)     First, none of the documents stated in the Unless Order were disclosed by 4 February 2022. A list of documents was only filed and served on 11 February 2022. Needless to say, inspection of documents was not completed by the 4 February 2022 deadline either (“**The Punctuality Breach**”).

> (b)     Second, even if the documents had been filed in time, they did not sufficiently fulfil Chua and Boon’s obligations under the Unless Order (“**The Sufficiency Breach**”).

In my view, both of these breaches have been made out.

### The Punctuality Breach

13     The starting point is that the list of documents was filed and served late. That would, strictly speaking, already amount to a breach of the Unless Order. To this, Chua’s ex-counsel’s (“**Ms Moynihan**”) explanation was that there had been some sort of error with the e-Litigation portal, and that the relevant documents had not been accepted by the portal.[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4) That was why Chua also filed DC/SUM 484/2022 (“**SUM 484**”) seeking an extension of time to file the relevant documents. Ms Moynihan’s explanation was believable and credible. Indeed, she exhibited contemporaneous emails suggesting that she genuinely believed that the list of documents had been filed and served by 4 February 2022. I accept her explanation in full and grant the extension of time sought in SUM 484.

14     But even then, the filing would still have been too late. The Unless Order required Chua and Boon to “comply fully” with the Discovery Order by 4 February 2022. That would mean that inspection ought to have been carried out and completed by then as well. Even if the documents had been filed by 4 February 2022 (Ms Moynihan’s email suggests that it was filed at about 10.56 pm on 4 February 2022),[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5) it would have been impossible for CAPL’s solicitors to have conducted the inspection by 4 February 2022.

15     It would, of course, sound petty to bemoan every late submission, and cry foul at every tardy filing. But this was not ordinary lateness. This was lateness in the face of an Unless Order where DR Lim had already given Chua and Boon a chance to make up for their poor conduct during discovery. And more importantly, trivial or not, this was still a lapse. The breach may well be minor and inconsequential, but that is something to be analysed at a later stage of the inquiry, for example when evaluating whether the possibility of a fair trial had been compromised. It does not change the fact that this was still a breach.

### The Sufficiency Breach

16     Beyond this, I find that the documents disclosed are themselves, insufficient to meet the obligations imposed by the Unless Order, save as to:

> (a)     Item 2 of Annex A (“All documents evidencing transactions between \[J&J\] and \[CAPL\]”);

> (b)     Item 4 of Annex A (“All bank account statements of \[J&J\]”); and

> (c)     the entirety of Annex B.

#### Annex A Documents (Items 2 and 4) and Annex B Documents

17     Item 4 of Annex A was disclosed. All of J&J’s bank statements between February 2011 and December 2019 were produced (albeit belatedly). This much was acknowledged by CAPL as well.[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6)

18     Item 2 of Annex A (the documents evidencing transactions between J&J and CAPL) were also disclosed. Though only five purchase orders were disclosed by Chua, I am satisfied that there was sufficient disclosure for this category of documents.

19     Admittedly, there is reason to believe that there were other transactions and accordingly, other documents related to those transactions. Indeed, Chua and Boon had acknowledged some $317,831.32 worth of transactions between J&J and CAPL in their Reply and Defence to Counterclaim (Amendment No. 2) (“RDCC”).[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7) However, I am inclined to believe Chua’s explanation that the rest of the documents were in CAPL’s rather than her possession. For one, CAPL was a party to these transactions. It stands to reason that CAPL would have possession of these documents. Additionally, any undisclosed documents relating to these transactions were arguably generated by CAPL itself since the reference numbers used to identify the transactions (the “Job CO numbers”) were internally generated by CAPL.[^8] CAPL denied that the Job CO numbers were internally generated,[^9] but the denial was unsubstantiated and unconvincing. As against this, Chua substantiated her assertion[^10] by reference to the primary documents themselves, showing that the Job CO Numbers used in CAPL’s Defence and Counterclaim (Amendment No. 1)[^11] were actually “CAPL Job No.”[^12] This proved that the Job CO numbers were internally generated by CAPL, raising a credible inference that CAPL did indeed create those documents and that they were in CAPL’s possession. For these reasons, I find Chua’s explanations here to be more believable than CAPL’s.

20     Granted, there was some basis to infer that Chua and Boon had the documents which evinced these transactions – they could not otherwise have stated this figure with such specificity.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13) But the truth is, it was CAPL that first raised this figure of $317,831.32 in its Defence and Counterclaim (Amendment No. 1) (“DNCC”).[^14] Chua and Boon merely parroted this figure in their RDCC as it “roughly \[accorded\] with what \[Chua recalled\] to be the revenue which was generated for CAPL by J&J”.[^15] In other words, there was a perfectly plausible explanation for why the RDCC stated such a specific sum of $317,831.32 as well.

21     As for the Annex B documents, I am prepared to accept that all of the documents relating to those categories had been disclosed to the best of Chua’s abilities. She had fully complied with the Unless Order in respect of these documents. This is for three reasons:

> (a)     CAPL itself acknowledged that some of these documents had been disclosed (albeit belatedly).[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16) These were Items 1, 3, 7 and 8 of Annex B.

> (b)     Some of the documents sought either did not exist or were disclosed in another form. These were Items 2, 4 and 5 of Annex B. CAPL had sought these documents based on a misunderstanding of the evidence (a misunderstanding which, to be fair to CAPL, was not necessarily by any fault of its own):

>> (i)       CAPL had assumed that the Plaintiff had sent an email to one Eva Yong on 10 July 2017at 1.33pm (Item 2 of Annex B).

>> (ii)       CAPL had also assumed that there had been a related email sent to one June Then on 10 July 2017 (Item 4 of Annex B).

>> (iii)       And finally, CAPL had assumed that a Supplier Aging List had been forwarded to Eva Yong as well (Item 5 of Annex B).

> All of these assumptions were based on the contents of a _draft_ email that Chua had prepared for Eva Yong on 10 July 2017 (_ie_. Item 2 of Annex B) but ultimately never sent. The _actual_ email sent was indeed disclosed.[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17) And from there, it was reasonably clear that no other email was sent to June Then (the email sought in Item 4 of Annex B). It was also clear that no mention was made of a Supplier Aging List (Item 5 of Annex B). In other words, Items 4 and 5 of Annex B did not exist. I am reasonably satisfied with these clarifications from Chua as there was sufficient contemporaneous evidence supporting the same. For example, she produced an email sent by one “Christopher” who helped review and amend the draft letter.[^18] In the circumstances, I find that the failure to disclose Items 2, 4 and 5 of Annex B was satisfactorily explained.

> (c)     Besides remarking that the emails produced were arranged somewhat haphazardly, CAPL has not taken issue with the sufficiency of the disclosure of Item 6 of Annex B. This much was clear both from Leong’s affidavit filed on 4 March 2022[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19) and from CAPL’s submissions filed on 7 March 2022.[^20]

22     Given the above, I find that Items 2 and 4 of Annex A and the entirety of Annex B were sufficiently disclosed.

#### Annex A Documents – Items 1, 3 and 6

23     As for Items 1, 3, and 6 of Annex A however, I find that there was inadequate disclosure and this much was acknowledged by Chua:

> (a)     in relation to Item 1 of Annex A (“I do acknowledge that the documents \[disclosed\] are not all the documents that could have existed between the time that I left CAPL to the time that I closed J&J in October 2019…”);[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21)

> (b)     in relation to Item 3 of Annex A (where she acknowledged that there were “other purchase orders from Yokogawa made before \[she\] left CAPL”[\[note: 22\]](#Ftn_22) which were not disclosed); and

> (c)     in relation to Item 6 of Annex A (“I accept the fact that the documents \[produced\] are not financial statements of J&J…”).[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23)

24     The real question then, was whether Chua’s explanations for her non-disclosure were credible. Broadly speaking, Chua offered three explanations for their failure to disclose these documents. None of these were convincing.

25     First, regarding J&J documents generated _before_ her resignation from CAPL, Chua claimed that she had left them behind when she left CAPL’s employ in July 2017.[\[note: 24\]](#Ftn_24) Her explanation was that J&J was CAPL’s business conduit – an entity set up on Leong’s (_ie_ CAPL’s) instructions for the purposes of helping CAPL generate work.[^25] All of J&J’s business was conducted under CAPL’s supervision. Accordingly, when Chua resigned, she left behind all of the J&J documents that had been generated up to that point with CAPL, since they were ostensibly CAPL’s property.

26     Without making a factual finding on this point, I am prepared to accept that there was some evidence of J&J operating as CAPL’s business conduit. The agenda for _CAPL’s_ 2015 Year End Meeting (as documented in an email dated 14 December 2015)[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26) describes J&J almost as an arm of CAPL, whose purpose was “to get jobs from Yokogawa panel department and some other new customers”. Additionally, _CAPL itself_ was able to provide a J&J Profit & Loss Statement in a related suit (HC/S 996/2021), presumably suggesting that J&J was operating under CAPL’s auspices at some point. All these – and I stress once again, that this does not amount to any sort of factual finding whatsoever – lent some credibility to Chua’s explanation.

27     Unfortunately, this was not enough to satisfactorily explain the non-disclosure of pre-resignation J&J documents. Even if J&J was CAPL’s business conduit, it does not necessarily follow that Chua would have left all J&J documents with CAPL when she resigned. For one, this was simply unbelievable. By Chua’s own admission,[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27) she was “continuing with some projects that were ongoing” at J&J even after she left CAPL. It was hard to imagine how she could have continued those projects if she had left all the documents relating to these projects behind at CAPL. In fact, Chua _did not_ leave behind all the J&J documents when she left CAPL. In her latest list of documents (dated 11 February 2022),[^28] she was able to disclose J&J purchase orders from 2012,[^29] quotations given by J&J in 2015[^30] and invoices billed to J&J in 2016[^31] – precisely the sort of pre-resignation documents that she had supposedly left behind at CAPL.

28     Moreover, this explanation depended on a fundamentally unstable premise: that any J&J documents generated before her resignation in 2017 were sent to her _CAPL_ email address. The documents showed that to be untrue – the 2015 quotations[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32) were sent to her personal email address and the 2016 invoices were also sent to XXX@gmail.com. This was unsurprising since J&J’s listed email address (in Boon’s application to register J&J as a new business firm) [^33] was Chua’s personal email address. In other words, at least some of J&J’s business was conducted through Chua’s personal email.

29     In the face of such overwhelming evidence, Chua’s counsel (“**Mr Liow**”) conceded that Chua’s first explanation did not fully explain all the documents that could have possibly been generated before she resigned from CAPL. His answer lay instead in the law. Chua had already dredged up all the documents that were in her personal email. She had produced all she could give. And she had deposed all this in her affidavit. Such testimony, at an interlocutory application such as in discovery proceedings, ordinarily benefited from a presumption of veracity. The Court ought to accept her affidavit as final and conclusive, and her word must not be contravened – at least until trial (_Soh Lup Chee_ at \[9\]).

30     But that argument forgets the exception to this rule. Where the existence or suppression of documents is itself an issue for determination at the trial of the action, these sorts of affidavits do not necessarily have to be regarded as conclusive and final: _Btech Engineering Pte Ltd v. Novellers Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] SGHC 171</span> at \[96\] (“_Btech Engineering_”), citing _Cephus Shipping Corp. v. Guardian Royal Exchange Assurance plc, “The Capricorn”_ \[1995\] 1 Lloyd’s Rep. 622 at 646:

> 96    … However, an important exception to his rule exists where the existence or suppression of documents is itself an issue for determination at the trial of the action (_The Capricorn_ at 646):

>> … The present application proceeds on the premise that, at trial, it is open to the defendants, as a matter of probability and on the basis of any useful answers they can extract in cross-examination of any witnesses who happen to be called on issues which do arise for determination, to undermine the affidavits of discovery given by Mr. Faraklas. I have more than a little doubt whether that can be so. The right view of Fayed v. Lonrho Ltd. may be that, unless the existence or suppression of documents is itself an issue for determination at trial of the action, affidavits of discovery remain conclusive and are subject to challenge by either party only in the limited circumstances identified in that case. In any other case, an application made under O. 24, r. 16 remains effectively interlocutory whether made before or at trial. …

31     That is precisely the case here. At least part of CAPL’s counterclaim, much like Novellers Pte Ltd’s counterclaim in _Btech Engineering_, was that Chua had unlawfully detained or removed some of CAPL’s documents.[\[note: 34\]](#Ftn_34) In such circumstances, the rationale for this presumption of veracity does not apply. As Choo JC explained in _Soh Lup Chee v Seow Boon Cheng_ <span class="citation">\[2002\] 1 SLR(R) 604</span> (“_Soh Lup Chee_”) at \[9\], affidavits raised in interlocutory discovery proceedings ordinarily “do not address the issues for trial and whether the deponent is truthful or not in respect of the discovery of documents he might still persuade the trial judge of the merits of his case through other evidence.” Such rationale being plainly inapplicable to the present case, I cannot see how this presumption can assist Chua at all.

32     If anything, I find it extremely difficult to believe Chua’s testimony. Her credibility had been severely damaged by her conduct in the proceedings. Granted, I have not had the benefit of observing Chua’s demeanour or hearing any oral testimony from her. But her inconsistent positions, as documented in the affidavits, speak for themselves. As I alluded to above at \[1\], Chua has constantly shifted her position on everything including the relevance of the documents sought, her possession of the same, and now, the very existence of these documents.

33     The following is a tabulation of the numerous inconsistent positions that Chua has taken in relation to Items 1, 2, 3, 4 and 6 of Annex A:

34     In the circumstances, I am neither convinced by Chua’s first explanation (if only because the weight of the evidence showed it to be patently false) nor could I accept Mr Liow’s reliance on any legal presumptions (if only because it did not apply to the present facts).

35     Even if my view of Chua’s first explanation is wrong or misguided, Chua would still have failed to adequately explain what happened to documents that were generated after her resignation in 2017. This brings me to her second explanation.

36     Chua’s second explanation was that she “did not keep any of those documents” after she terminated J&J in October 2019.[\[note: 72\]](#Ftn_72) This was her stated reason for discarding these documents:[^73]

> “This was because I was not aware of any legal requirement to keep copies of those documents; my understanding was that as a \[_sic_\] J&J was a sole proprietorship, it did not need to have its accounts audited and since J&J did not make any profit in time \[_sic_\] that I left CAPL to the time that I closed J&J, I did not think that I needed to keep those documents”

37     Besides being incoherent (there was no logical connection between J&J’s profitability and the decision to dispose the documents), this explanation was not satisfactory at all. This suit commenced in 2018. The first version of the Defence and Counterclaim was filed on 10 April 2018. Chua would have known the gist of the counterclaim early on. Chua would have known of her discovery obligations since she had the benefit of legal advice all along. Chua would have known that, based on CAPL’s counterclaim and pursuant to her discovery obligations, those documents were highly relevant to the proceedings. Instead, she dumped them.

38     In my view, this was a damning admission rather than a satisfactory explanation. In fact, Mr Liow himself acknowledged that this was “no good answer \[and that\] the best answer is that \[Chua\] wasn’t thinking”. He was also candid in acknowledging that Chua had effectively breached her discovery obligations (although he stressed that this did not amount to a breach of the Unless Order since the Unless Order was made after the alleged disposal). In these circumstances, there is simply no reason for me to accept Chua’s second explanation.

39     Chua’s third explanation did not assist her either. That explanation pertained specifically to Item 6 of Annex A. She claimed that J&J did not “keep its accounts”[\[note: 74\]](#Ftn_74) and that there were “no formal accounts prepared for J&J since there was no need to audit any accounts of J&J”.[^75] An officer from the Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore (“**IRAS**”) had also supposedly informed Boon that “since \[J&J was\] a sole proprietorship company \[…\] no income tax filing or reporting was required for J&J”.[^76] In other words, Chua’s explanation was that J&J’s financial statements had never existed in the first place. I reject this explanation for three reasons.

> (a)     It is inconceivable that a company such as J&J, taking into account the volume and value of transactions it engaged in, would have been run without the barest semblance of a ledger. The J&J cheque stubs produced by Chua show a large number of transactions, involving many counterparties and for sums ranging anywhere between $68.48 to $20,000.[\[note: 77\]](#Ftn_77) J&J’s bank statements show deposits amounting to a sum of at least $2,071,251.26 and withdrawals amounting to a sum of at least $2,022,030.74.[^78] It is unbelievable that there would not even be informal accounts/statements relating to J&J’s business. I note that a similar sort of inference was drawn by Choo Han Teck JC (as his honour then was), in _Soh Lup Chee_ at \[7\].

> (b)     As DR Lim mentioned in her oral judgment, income tax is payable on Boon’s business income from J&J pursuant to section 10(1) of the Income Tax Act 1947, and such business income must be reported in Form B (Self Employed). For Boon to meet such annual reporting obligations, he would require J&J’s financial statements so as to ascertain whether J&J made a profit which he had to declare as income. Moreover, he had the necessary source documents required to prepare J&J’s financial statements. It is no answer for Boon to claim that some IRAS officer had released him from his reporting obligations. This was a bare and unsubstantiated assertion. Even with the usual presumption of veracity that attaches to affidavits made during discovery (_Singapore Civil Procedure 2021_ vol 1 (Cavinder Bull gen ed) (Sweet & Maxwell, 2021) at para 24/16/3 (“_The White Book_”); _Soh Lup Chee_ at \[9\]), I find Boon’s testimony difficult to believe, especially given the clear statutory requirements for him to declare his income.

> (c)     No reason was given for why this explanation was only offered at such a late stage in the proceedings. Indeed, if there had been no formal accounts prepared at all, I would have expected that to have been Chua and Boon’s position from the very start. In view of the belatedness of this explanation and the complete failure to give any reasonable clarification for the belatedness, I am deeply sceptical of this explanation.

40     For these reasons, Chua has failed to adequately explain her non-disclosure of documents and had, as a result, breached the Unless Order.

41     In fairness to Chua, there was a fourth (somewhat subtler) argument alluded to in the hearing: as unbelievable or as unsatisfactory as Chua’s explanations were, she had still done her best to comply with the Unless Order. Yes, the first explanation was unbelievable since she clearly had possession of certain J&J documents generated prior to her resignation from CAPL. Yes, the second explanation was unsatisfactory since she had effectively admitted to disposing of an entire class of highly relevant documents. But she had since produced what little she had on hand. She had done her best to, as Mr Liow put it, “make things right”. All this, she had put on affidavit as well. That, arguably, was enough to fulfil her obligations under the Unless Order.

42     This argument missed the point. She should never have destroyed documents in the first place. And I am loath to accept this argument because it creates a real moral hazard for delinquent litigants who could seek to excuse unacceptable conduct (such as the destruction of documents) by later claiming that they had tried to “make things right”. Of course, the law should give litigants an opportunity to make amends. That is why the Unless Order was granted to begin with. But when a litigant responds to such indulgence with an outright admission that she had _destroyed_ documents, I could not see how that could be overlooked. It cannot be that a litigant can get away with such egregious conduct by giving the few scraps that remain after a purge. Of course, in approaching this application, I am required to give the benefit of doubt in the construction of the order to the plaintiff whose action faces the prospect of being dismissed (_The White Book_ 24/16/3). But there was nothing ambiguous about the terms of the Unless Order and no amount of creative construction of its terms could excuse Chua’s behaviour. Whatever Mr Liow’s quibble with the “broadness of the Discovery Order”, the fact remains that Chua and Boon have not appealed against the Discovery Order itself. By this stage, it was too late to cry foul at a supposedly broad (the implication: unfair) discovery order.

43     Most importantly, and quite separately from the believability of her explanations, I find that Chua’s own credibility had been severely damaged by her conduct in the proceedings (see \[33\] above). Based on what I have mentioned above, I find that Chua was evasive and shifty during discovery. Her latest set of positions in relation to these documents (as documented primarily in her affidavit dated 25 March 2022) further cemented that impression, and ultimately fortified my decision that there had been a breach of the Unless Order.

## Issue 2: Whether the Claim and Defence to Counterclaim ought to be struck out

### The applicable law

44     There was little disagreement between counsel about the applicable law. A full and comprehensive exposition of the law relating to striking out of pleadings for breaches of discovery obligations was laid out by the Court of Appeal in _Mitora._ For present purposes, the following three principles are most applicable:

> (a)     Although “the breach of an “unless order” will automatically trigger its specified adverse consequences” (_Mitora_ at \[35\]), and even if “it has been established that an intentional and contumelious breach of an “unless order” had been committed, the court must nevertheless determine what sanction should be imposed as a result” (_Mitora_ at \[37\]);

> (b)     When an “unless order” has been breached, “\[t\]he onus will then be on the defaulting party to demonstrate that the breach had not been intentional and contumelious so as to avoid those consequences _Mitora_ at \[35\]); more fundamentally “the party seeking to escape the consequences of his default must show that he had made positive efforts to comply but was prevented from doing so by extraneous circumstances” (_Syed Mohamed Abdul Muthaliff and another v Arjan Bhisham Chotrani_ \[1999\] 1 SLR(R) 36; _Mitora_ at \[36\]);

> (c)     “Although the normal prerequisite for the striking out of an action under r.16 is the existence of areal or substantial or serious risk that a fair trial will no longer be possible, in cases of contumacious conduct, the deliberate destruction or suppression of a document or the persistent disregard of an order of production would engage the court’s jurisdiction and justify a striking-out order even where a fair trial was still possible. Wilful disobedience is not required, as a failure to comply with court orders through negligence, incompetence or sheer indolence may justify a striking out” (_The White Book_ at para 24/16/1; _Mitora_ at \[48\]). In that regard, “an action or defence can be struck out for failure to make discovery of documents even if the defaulting party rectifies his non-compliance” (_Mitora_ at \[47\]).

### The analysis

45     As a starting point, Chua and Boon have not pointed to any extraneous circumstance that justified their non-disclosure. If anything, the non-disclosure was entirely attributable to their own actions. It was Chua who had disposed of all the J&J documents generated post-resignation. It was Boon who had failed to keep any financial statements. And it was Chua who had, despite legal advice throughout the entire proceedings, only produced documents when pressed. Bank statements were produced only after the Unless Order was given; cheque stubs were only produced after CAPL initiated SUM 541; and all this after Chua flatly denied possession of documents which she was later able to produce (_eg._ purchase orders between J&J and CAPL, or the purchase order from Yokogawa).

46     It is no answer to say that she was “not aware of any legal requirement to keep copies of those documents”.[\[note: 79\]](#Ftn_79) Admittedly, I am not prepared to conclude that there was a deliberate suppression of documents (although I note that DR Lim took a far less charitable view when granting the Unless Order). But even assuming the best of Chua’s intentions, “a failure to comply with court orders through negligence, incompetence or sheer indolence may justify a striking out” (_The White Book_ at para 24/16/1; _Mitora_ at \[48\]). It is also no answer to point to the cheque stubs – the latest set of documents that were produced – to say that things have finally been made right (see above at \[42\]); an action or defence can be struck out for failure to make discovery of documents even if the defaulting party rectifies her non-compliance: _Mitora_ at \[47\].

47     Notwithstanding the above, I am not prepared to strike out all of Chua and Boon’s pleadings. As I alluded to above at \[2\], the orders sought by CAPL were disproportionate to the actual prejudice experienced. Yes, the Unless Order stated that a breach should result in the striking out of both the claim and defence to counterclaim. But I am not obliged to blindly impose that specified sanction (indeed, that was the Court of Appeal’s view in _Mitora_ as well).

48     In that regard, I gratefully accept Mr Liow’s invitation to study the actual prejudice that has resulted from this non-disclosure. That inquiry, as Mr Liow rightly pointed out, should have reference to the pleadings themselves and examine for which of the causes of action a fair trial would be prejudiced. Mr Liow’s (admittedly attractive) submission was that the documents not disclosed related only to the _quantum of damages_ that CAPL stood to be awarded, should it prove successful at trial. Liability itself, could be adjudicated by reference to what had already been produced: Chua had already admitted, in some sense, that J&J had conducted business with Yokogawa after she resigned from CAPL; and CAPL already knew who J&J’s clients were, based on source documents such as the bank statements and cheque stubs. The documents sought in discovery, even if produced, would not assist CAPL in prosecuting its counterclaim.[\[note: 80\]](#Ftn_80)_Ergo_, even absent these documents, a fair trial is still possible.

49     I am unable to agree. CAPL was interested in more than just the _identities_ of those that J&J did business with. It was (rightfully, in my view) concerned with the _circumstances_ in which J&J entered into business with those partners. That would have been crucial to proving CAPL’s central claim that J&J was siphoning business that rightfully belonged to CAPL. And those documents (for example, correspondence between J&J and its business partners, disclosed pursuant to Item 1 of Annex A) could have gone towards showing that.

50     Mr Liow conceded this point but submitted that these businesses (whose custom J&J had allegedly stolen from CAPL) could always be summoned by CAPL for examination at trial or asked to produce documents relating to the circumstances in which they entered into business with J&J. But the only reason why these _third parties_ might have to appear at trial or produce documents is because Chua dumped the evidence in the first place. It cannot be that CAPL should be expected to remedy J&J’s wrongs.

51     And in any case, if one were to study the specific causes of action listed in the counterclaim, it would be clear that there were a couple of key factual allegations that underpinned them. The non-disclosure of the documents in Items 1, 3 and 6 of Annex A _directly_ pertained to some of those factual allegations and the failure to produce the documents would seriously hamper CAPL’s ability to prove those facts.

52     In that sense, it would be helpful to list out the parties’ claims and the main factual allegations underpinning each of these claims:

> (a)     Chua’s claim for $13,000, such sum allegedly being unpaid salary she is owed (“**the Salary Claim**”);[\[note: 81\]](#Ftn_81)

> (b)     CAPL’s claim that Chua had breached her duties as CAPL’s director and/or her obligation as trustee of its assets/properties by

>> (i)       failing to return/hand over its confidential documents upon her resignation (“**the Handover Allegation**”);[\[note: 82\]](#Ftn_82)

>> (ii)       failing to account to Leong about CAPL’s day-to-day business operations (“**the Accountability Allegation**”);[\[note: 83\]](#Ftn_83)

>> (iii)       wrongfully removing/deleting documents belonging to CAPL (“**the Disposal Allegation”**);[\[note: 84\]](#Ftn_84)

>> (iv)       setting up and operating J&J as a competing business (“**the Competing Business Allegation**”);[\[note: 85\]](#Ftn_85)

>> (v)       failing to disclose her interest in J&J to CAPL (“**the Disclosure Allegation**”);[\[note: 86\]](#Ftn_86)

>> (vi)       causing CAPL to supply manpower and materials to J&J at an undervalue (“**the Undervalue Allegation**”);[\[note: 87\]](#Ftn_87)

>> (vii)       communicating CAPL’s confidential information to third parties like Boon and J&J (“**the 3P Communication Allegation**”);[\[note: 88\]](#Ftn_88)

> (c)     CAPL’s claim in unlawful means conspiracy, to the effect that Chua had conspired with Boon to defraud CAPL[\[note: 89\]](#Ftn_89) by:

>> (i)       setting up and operating J&J as a competing business (effectively the Competing Business Allegation);[\[note: 90\]](#Ftn_90)

>> (ii)       failing to disclose J&J’s registration to CAPL (an extension of the Non-disclosure Allegation);[\[note: 91\]](#Ftn_91)

>> (iii)       wrongfully diverting projects away from CAPL to J&J (“**the Diversion Allegation**”);[\[note: 92\]](#Ftn_92)

>> (iv)       causing CAPL to supply manpower and materials to J&J at an undervalue (effectively the Undervalue Allegation);[\[note: 93\]](#Ftn_93)

>> (v)       continuing to retain CAPL’s confidential information (an extension of the Handover Allegation);[\[note: 94\]](#Ftn_94)

>> (vi)       communicating such confidential information to third parties like Boon and J&J (effectively the 3P Communication Allegation);[\[note: 95\]](#Ftn_95)

>> (vii)       inducing one of CAPL’s employee (“**Peong**”), to work for J&J (“**the Peong Allegation**”);[\[note: 96\]](#Ftn_96)

> (d)     CAPL’s claim that Boon was a “constructive trustee for the Defendant”[\[note: 97\]](#Ftn_97) as he had knowing receipt of the proceeds from:

>> (i)       CAPL’s supply of services and materials to J&J at an undervalue (premised on the Undervalue Allegation);[\[note: 98\]](#Ftn_98)

>> (ii)       CAPL’s supply of services and material to J&J without proper disclosure of the actual value of such services/materials (premised on the Non-disclosure Allegation);[\[note: 99\]](#Ftn_99)

>> (iii)       Chua’s breaches of her director’s duties and/or obligations as trustee of CAPL’s properties/assets.[\[note: 100\]](#Ftn_100)

> (e)     CAPL’s claim that Boon and Chua had unlawfully interfered with its business by:

>> (i)       setting up J&J to compete with CAPL (effectively the Competing Business Allegation);[\[note: 101\]](#Ftn_101) and

>> (ii)       inducing Peong to work for J&J (effectively the Peong Allegation);[\[note: 102\]](#Ftn_102)

53     Thus organised, the claims/counterclaims in this suit could be reduced to a couple of key factual allegations. For clarity, I’ve provided a summary as follows:

![](data:image;base64,)

54     So understood, it seems to me that certain facts could still be fairly determined at trial without any of the documents sought. For example, a fair trial remains possible for the Salary Claim. Judging by the pleadings, the crucial questions for this claim would be:

> (a)     whether, according to the terms of the Contract, Chua is entitled to salary for July and August 2017; and

> (b)     the precise terms of her arrangement with Leong to take half days off every Tuesday and Thursday (“**the Half-Day Arrangement**”); namely, whether the arrangement extended beyond March 2017 and if so, whether she had been expected to consume her leave for that.

55     The adjudication of these issues does not require the documents stated in the Discovery Order. If anything, CAPL will, in all likelihood, have access to the relevant documents. It will have Chua’s Employment Contract (as certainly seems to be the case, given that there was extensive quotation from the same in its Defence). It will have Chua’s leave records, which would have documented Chua’s authorised absences. It will also have any communications between Chua and either HR or Leong about the terms of this Half-Day Arrangement. If it was an entirely oral agreement, evidence can be sought through interrogatories or, more realistically, through testimony at trial. Either way, fair trial of the Salary Claim has not been prejudiced in any way.

56     However, for some of the other factual allegations, I would imagine CAPL would be significantly disabled by the non-disclosure of these documents. For example:

> (a)     The Diversion Allegation – naturally, any sort of correspondence between J&J and its business partners (discoverable pursuant to Item 1 of Annex A) would have shed light on the circumstances under which the impugned transactions were initiated/carried out. That would have gone some way towards showing whether Chua had indeed wrongfully diverted projects away from CAPL.

> (b)     The Accountability Allegation – any financial statement from J&J (discoverable pursuant to Item 6 of Annex A) would have revealed the profits it had made and allowed CAPL to verify whether Chua had indeed accounted to CAPL regarding the same.

> (c)     The Competing Business Allegation – purchase orders and invoices (discoverable pursuant to Item 1 and 3 of Annex A) would have shown the _type_ of jobs that J&J carried out after Chua left CAPL, and whether these were the sort of projects that CAPL was involved with as well (_ie_ whether J&J was indeed a competing business).

57     Notably, these particular factual allegations pertained to the causes of action stated in CAPL’s counterclaim. In my view, CAPL would be seriously prejudiced in prosecuting its counterclaim as some of the factual building blocks are simply not available anymore. In the circumstances, I concluded that a fair trial was not possible for CAPL’s counterclaims and accordingly, struck out Chua and Boon’s Defence to Counterclaim.

## Conclusion

58     In summary, I partially grant the orders sought in SUM 484 (by striking out only Chua and Boon’s Defence to Counterclaim). I also grant the extension of time sought in SUM 541 but ultimately this had no practical implication for whether there had indeed been a breach of the Unless Order.

59     On a concluding note, I wish to record my deep gratitude to both counsel for their able submissions, both written and oral, which I found to be immensely helpful.

60     I will hear the parties on costs.
